WASHINCTON-U. S. Supreme
Court denied a hearing to three
Baton Rouge, La, city officials
who lost a suit for an order bar
ring the Congress Of Racial
Equality from demonstrating
there.


Federal District Judge E.Gor-
don West of Baton Rouge, Is
sued an Injunction against CORE
demonstrations but 1t was set
aside by the 5th u .S.Circuit Court
of Appeals.


City officials used the 18th
Amendment to the Constitution,
their complaint state CORE was
preventing them from providing
the ",equal protection of the laws"
to- all persons.


The case grew from demon
strations by Negro students from
Southern University in 1861.

out heavyweight champion Sonny
Liston In five rounds, three short

as he told reporters Liston was

was the centerpiece.

having your birthday early. have

sonally."

Who eats the most meat7


Not Americans, as you might
think. Leading in per capita meat
consumption Is New Zealand,
where each person averages 235
pounds a year. Australians eat
22l pounds; Uruguayans, 2l3
pounds: and Argentinians. 2O2

Americans come next, the US.

with an annual per capita con-
sumption of l64 pounds a year.

JACKSONVILLE, FLA. In
tegration of Negro and white
teachers and their pupils, has
been ordered for this city and
surrounding Duval county by the
us. 5th Circuit Court of APP
peals.


Jack Greenberg, director
counsel of the NAACP Legal
Defense and Educational Fund,
announced.


This marks the first Appeals
Court ruling since the historic
1854 Supreme Court school in
tegration decision, that specifi-
cally includes administrative and
teaching personnel


The three Judge court also
ordered an end to separate bud
gets, employment and construc-
tion contracts, curricula and pro-
gram.


Mr.. Creenberg said that this is
a "most sweeping school int
grafton victory. The court grant
ed every request in our prayers
for relief"


The case was argued before
the Court Of Appeals by Earl
M. Johnson of Jacks onville, one
of the Fund 8 cooperating attor-
neys. Constance Baker Motley
and Leroy C. Clark of the Fund s
New York City headquarters,
we're counsel.


The Fund S lawyers pointed out
that in some instances, some of
the minor plaintiffs and other
minor Negroes are required to
travel twenty miles to attend
Negro schools, whereas they re-
side much nearer a white school.





The Court of Appeals ruling
also calls for an end Of the
following practices in Jackson
Vile and Duval county schools:


*biracial school system


dual scheme or pattern of
school zone lines or attendance
area lines based on race and
color.


school assignment of in
dividual pupils by race


assignment of teachers,
principals and other profession
al staff on basis of race.


Legal Defense attorneys filed
the suit in behalf of Is Jackson
Vile youngsters and "on behalf
of all Negro children and parents
in Duval county who are SINH
larly situated"


There are presently 81 white
and "a Negro schools in the
county.

From February on it's time to
watch for signs of new life on
the plants you put away in cool,
dark place last fall. Gradually
acclimate the plants to warmth
and sunlight, then start using
plant food.
